sms chosen to solve them.  Let's please keep the<br />&gt; discussions technical.  That's the best way to reach a viable<br />&gt; long-term solution which can benefit a lot wider audience in the long<br />&gt; term.  Even though that might not be the path of least immediate<br />&gt; resistance, I believe that google will be an eventual beneficiary too.<br /><br />So here's a somewhat odd request I got to hear very recently (at<br />LinuxCon EU in Ireland)..<br /><br />A least some game engine writers apparently would like to be able to<br />set scheduling priorities for threads within a single process, because<br />they may want te game as a whole to have a certain priority, but then<br />some of the threads are critical for latency and may want certain<br />guaranteed resources (eg audio or actual gameplay) while others are<br />very much background things (garbage collection etc).<br /><br />I suspect that's a very non-google use. We apparently don't really<br />support that kind of per-thread model right now at all.<br /><br />Do they want cgroups? Maybe not. You can apparently do something like<br />this under Windows and OS X, but not under Linux (and I'm reporting<br />second-hand here, I don't know the exact details). I'm just bringing<br />it up as a somewhat unusual non-server thing that is certainly very<br />relevant despite being different.<br /><br />                 Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
